edu.rit.pj2.vbl

Class BitSet32Vbl

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.rit.util.BitSet32
      • edu.rit.pj2.vbl.BitSet32Vbl
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Streamable, Vbl, Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BitSet32Vbl.Intersection, BitSet32Vbl.MaxSize, BitSet32Vbl.MinSize, BitSet32Vbl.Union

    public class BitSet32Vbl
extends BitSet32
implements Vbl
    Class BitSet32Vbl provides a reduction variable for a set of integers from 0 to 31 shared by multiple threads executing a ParallelStatement.

    The set elements are stored in a bitmap representation. The bitmap representation is a value of type int. Bit 0 of the bitmap (the least significant bit) corresponds to set element 0, bit 1 of the bitmap (the next least significant bit) corresponds to set element 1, and so on. A bit of the bitmap is 1 if the set contains the corresponding element; a bit of the bitmap is 0 if the set does not contain the corresponding element.

    Class BitSet32Vbl supports the parallel reduction pattern. Each thread creates a thread-local copy of the shared variable by calling the threadLocal() method of class Loop or the threadLocal() method of class Section. Each thread performs operations on its own copy, without needing to synchronize with the other threads. At the end of the parallel statement, the thread-local copies are automatically reduced together, and the result is stored in the original shared variable. The reduction is performed by the shared variable's reduce() method.

    The following subclasses provide various predefined reduction operations. You can also define your own subclasses with customized reduction operations.

    • Minimum size -- Class BitSet32Vbl.MinSize
    • Maximum size -- Class BitSet32Vbl.MaxSize
    • Set union -- Class BitSet32Vbl.Union
    • Set intersection -- Class BitSet32Vbl.Intersection

      • reduce

        public void reduce(Vbl vbl)
        Reduce the given shared variable into this shared variable. The two variables are combined together, and the result is stored in this shared variable. The reduce() method does not need to be multiple thread safe (thread synchronization is handled by the caller).

        The BitSet32Vbl base class's reduce() method leaves this shared variable unchanged.

        Specified by:
        reduce in interface Vbl
        Parameters:
        vbl - Shared variable.
        Throws:
        ClassCastException - (unchecked exception) Thrown if the class of vbl is not compatible with the class of this shared variable.
